# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: condenser-heat-transfer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] An **absorption-compression heat pump** (**ACHP**) is a device that integrate an electric compressor in an absorption heat pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In some cases this is obtained by combining a vapor-compression heat pump and an absorption heat pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] It is also referred to as a hybrid heat pump which is however a broader field.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Thanks to this integration, the device can obtain cooling and heating effects using both thermal and electrical energy sources.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This type of systems is well coupled with cogeneration systems where both heat and electricity are produced.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Depending on the configuration, the system can maximize heating and cooling production from a given amount of fuel, or can improve the temperature (hence the quality) of waste heat from other processes.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This second use is the most studied one and has been applied to several industrial applications.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The first absorption-compression heat pump cycle concept was patented by Osenbrück.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Little research on it was done in the following years.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] in the 70s, the energy saving potential of the cycle grew in interest and there was a rapid increase in research activities in the field.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In this period several experimental plants were built and in 1997, Groll summarized this activities in its review where he identified more than 40 studies.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] At that time, considerable work was still needed before the ACHP could become commercially available.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Nordtvedt studied the cycle in his doctoral thesis and his studies ended up in the construction, in 2011, of the first commercial application in the Norwegian Food Industry.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] After this, several units have been installed for commercial use in various high temperature industrial applications.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantage with respect to compression heat pump is that the compression-absorption heat pumps allow the heat to be transfer with a temperature glide.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The compression heat pump uses a single pure working fluid, hence exchanges heat at a constant temperature.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption-compression heat pump uses instead a binary mixture where the condensation and evaporation occur with a temperature glide.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This property increases the efficiency of the heat transfer when the heat source also has a significant temperature glide, which is the typical condition found when dealing with waste heat recovery.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Being a hybrid solution that can exploit both heat and mechanical/electric energy sources, the device can be perfectly coupled with cogeneration units to produce heating and cooling at very high efficiencies.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Moreover, it makes the system more flexible, allowing the optimization of the mix of electricity and thermal energy.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Their availability vary in fact along the day and the year.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Therefore the flexibility allow to reduce the operating costs.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main drawback of this technology is that, to achieve good performances, they typically need to employ ammonia, which is very toxic and flammable.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This drawback resulted in the fact that these applications remained limited to the industrial sector, where it is more practical dealing with dangerous fluids.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most studied configuration is the so-called *compression heat pump with solution cycle* (CHPS) or *compression resorption heat pump* (CRHP), where the compressor is in parallel to the electric pump located between the absorber and the desorber.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration is used to increase the temperature of waste heat since it allow high absorption temperature at lower pressure than compression heat pumps.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Another possible configuration for the absorption compression heat pump is obtained from the combination of a gas-driven absorption heat pump (GAHP) with a vapor-compression heat pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration arises from the consideration that both cycles have in common a condenser, a lamination valve, and an evaporator.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main difference between the two is in the compression phase: where the compression heat pump uses an electric compressor, the gas-driven absorption heat pump uses a thermal compressor.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The ACHP is obtained by combining the components that are in common and using the electric and thermal compressor in parallel or in series.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Compression heat pumps use only a single fluid which is a refrigerant.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In contrast, absorption heat pump requires two fluids, a refrigerant and an absorbent able to absorb it.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] By combining the two devices, proper refrigerant absorbent pairs compatible with both the cycles are needed.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] There is a wide choice of refrigerants available for compression heat pumps.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption cycle is the one limiting the choice of the refrigerant.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most common refrigerants for absorption systems are ammonia and water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Both are good for combined absorption-compression heat pumps.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ammonia has an exceptionally good solubility in water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This is an important aspect that increases the performance and decreases the size of the device.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] However, its high toxicity and flammability reduces its attractiveness.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Water is a very attractive refrigerant because it is abundant, non-toxic, non-flammable and highly soluble in lithium bromide (LiBr).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main issue with water is that, at the typical heat pump evaporator pressures, it freezes at 0 °C.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This makes water unsuitable for the applications where the cold sink goes below 0 °C, which is the typical winter operating condition of an air source heat pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorbent and refrigerant are strictly related to each other.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that ammonia is used as refrigerant, the most common absorbent is water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that water is used as refrigerant, as previously mentioned, the absorbent is usually LiBr.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ionic liquids have also been proposed as good absorbents, specially for water as refrigerant.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantages of these salts is that they can be used under the conditions at which LiBr solution runs the risk of crystallization and they are less corrosive.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] An **air-mixing plenum** (or mixing box) is used in building services engineering and HVAC construction for mixing air from different ductwork systems.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Air streams are mixed to save energy and improve energy efficiency by partially recirculating conditioned air.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] The most common application for an air-mixing plenum is the mixing of *return air* (or *extract air*) with fresh air to provide a supply air mixture for onward distribution to the building or area which the ventilation system is serving.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] The air transferred from the return air stream to the supply air stream is termed *recirculated air*.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] All air not mixed is rejected to the atmosphere as *exhaust air*.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] The mixing plenum normally combines two air streams, and includes for three sets of dampers: one for the fresh air, one for the exhaust air, and a mixing damper between the two air streams.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] The mix of fresh air and recirculated air can thus be adjusted to suit the needs of the building's occupants.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Most systems will use motorized dampers to control the air mixing, and controlled by the building management system (BMS), or controls system.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Typically as the fresh air and exhaust air dampers are driven from 0% open to 100% open, the mixing damper will in turn be driven from 100% open to 0% open, so as to always ensure a constant volume of supply and extract air.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Air supply to a building is generally performed by an air handling unit.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] The process may include filtering, heating, cooling, humidification, or dehumidification, all of which consume energy.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Since building occupants demand less than 100% fresh air, only a fraction of that amount is admitted to the system, with and equal amount of treated air exhausted to the atmosphere; fresh air is mixed with conditioned air in a plenum.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Enhanced controls systems may monitor the return air quality or carbon dioxide concentration in order to automatically modulate the air mix for optimum energy efficiency while maintaining desired fresh air requirements.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Such systems work very well in buildings where the occupancy rate can vary greatly throughout the day, or seasonally.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Additionally, when outside air conditions are such, typically mid-season weather conditions, it may be that ambient temperatures are suitable for free cooling purposes.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] In such conditions the mixing damper will be set to close and the system use full fresh air for optimum energy efficiency.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/air-mixing-plenum] Where fresh air is not required, such as early morning pre-heat or pre-conditioning periods, the mixing damper can be automatically set to full recirculation, again for optimum energy efficiency.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] The **ASHRAE Handbook** is the four-volume flagship publication of the nonprofit technical organization **ASHRAE** (**American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers**).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] This Handbook is considered the most comprehensive and authoritative repository of practical knowledge on the various topics that form the field of heating, ventilation, air-conditioning, and refrigeration (HVAC&R).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] The four volumes are *Fundamentals*, *Refrigeration*, *HVAC Applications* ("Applications"), and *HVAC Systems and Equipment* ("Systems and Equipment").
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] Members of ASHRAE receive the current volume, in both print and CD-ROM form, each year as a basic membership benefit.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] An enhanced electronic version, known as *ASHRAE Handbook Online* is a web-based version updated annually that contains the four latest volumes as well as extra content such as calculations, demonstration videos, and spreadsheets.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] The various versions of the Handbook are typically available to the public via technical, and other, libraries and bookstores.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] The ASHRAE Handbook has had a variety of titles.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] It began in 1922 as the **ASH&VE Guide**.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] In 1973 it became the ASHRAE Handbook, and in 1985 separate publication of inch-pound (I-P) and international system (SI) units versions of the volumes began.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] Stephen Comstock, and the Editor is Mark S.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook is published by ASHRAE from its headquarters in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook's content is created and modified by volunteers via ASHRAE's many Technical Committees (TCs), and then edited and formatted by professional staff at ASHRAE.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] For example, three chapters, in three different volumes, are maintained by TC 5.3, Room Air Distribution.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] Each chapter within a particular volume is reviewed and revised in a repeating four-year cycle; one volume is printed each year.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] In the summer of 2017 the new Fundamentals' volume was released.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] ASHRAE's Handbook Committee maintains an *Authors and Revisers Guide,* which can be obtained freely via the Handbook portion of the ASHRAE Web site.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] While each new or revised chapter manuscript is to be reviewed for technical content by each TC voting and corresponding member before publication, there are often many other pre- and post-publication reviewers.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] For example, members of the Society's Handbook Committee and the College of Fellows review chapters each year.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae-handbook] Reviews, from basic comments to detailed new content, are encouraged from all users of the Handbook and may be submitted through an online commenting system.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] In systems involving heat transfer, a **condenser** is a heat exchanger used to condense a gaseous substance into a liquid state through cooling.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] In doing so, the latent heat is released by the substance and transferred to the surrounding environment.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Condensers are used for efficient heat rejection in many industrial systems.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Condensers can be made according to numerous designs and come in many sizes ranging from rather small (hand-held) to very large (industrial-scale units used in plant processes).
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] For example, a refrigerator uses a condenser to get rid of heat extracted from the interior of the unit to the outside air.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Condensers are used in air conditioning, industrial chemical processes such as distillation, steam power plants, and other heat-exchange systems.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The use of cooling water or surrounding air as the coolant is common in many condensers.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The earliest laboratory condenser, a "Gegenstromkühler" (counter-flow condenser), was invented in 1771 by the Swedish-German chemist Christian Weigel.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] By the mid-19th century, German chemist Justus von Liebig would provide his own improvements on the preceding designs of Weigel and Johann Friedrich August Göttling, with the device becoming known as the Liebig condenser.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] A condenser is designed to transfer heat from a working fluid (e.g. water in a steam power plant) to a secondary fluid or the surrounding air.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The condenser relies on the efficient heat transfer that occurs during phase changes, in this case during the condensation of a vapor into a liquid.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The vapor typically enters the condenser at a temperature above that of the secondary fluid.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] As the vapor cools, it reaches the saturation temperature, condenses into liquid, and releases large quantities of latent heat.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] As this process occurs along the condenser, the quantity of vapor decreases and the quantity of liquid increases; at the outlet of the condenser, only liquid remains.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Some condenser designs contain an additional length to subcool this condensed liquid below the saturation temperature.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Countless variations exist in condenser design, with design variables including the working fluid, the secondary fluid, the geometry, and the material.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Common secondary fluids include water, air, refrigerants, or phase-change materials.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] A surface condenser is one in which condensing medium and vapors are physically separated and used when direct contact is not desired.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] It is a shell and tube heat exchanger installed at the outlet of every steam turbine in thermal power stations.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Commonly, the cooling water flows through the tube side and the steam enters the shell side where the condensation occurs on the outside of the heat transfer tubes.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The condensate drips down and collects at the bottom, often in a built-in pan called a *hotwell*.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The shell side often operates at a vacuum or partial vacuum, produced by the difference in specific volume between the steam and condensate.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Conversely, the vapor can be fed through the tubes with the coolant water or air flowing around the outside.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] In chemistry, a condenser is the apparatus that cools hot vapors, causing them to condense into a liquid.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Examples include the Liebig condenser, Graham condenser, and Allihn condenser.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] This is not to be confused with a condensation reaction which links two fragments into a single molecule by an addition reaction and an elimination reaction.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] In laboratory distillation, reflux, and rotary evaporators, several types of condensers are commonly used.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The Liebig condenser is simply a straight tube within a cooling water jacket and is the simplest (and relatively least expensive) form of condenser.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The Graham condenser is a spiral tube within a water jacket, and the Allihn condenser has a series of large and small constrictions on the inside tube, each increasing the surface area upon which the vapor constituents may condense.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Being more complex shapes to manufacture, these latter types are also more expensive to purchase.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] These three types of condensers are laboratory glassware items since they are typically made of glass.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Commercially available condensers usually are fitted with ground glass joints and come in standard lengths of 100, 200, and 400 mm.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Air-cooled condensers are unjacketed, while water-cooled condensers contain a jacket for the water.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Larger condensers are also used in industrial-scale distillation processes to cool distilled vapor into liquid distillate.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Commonly, the coolant flows through the tube side and distilled vapor through the shell side with distillate collecting at or flowing out the bottom.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] A typical configuration of such a condenser unit is as follows: The heat exchanger section wraps around the sides of the unit with the compressor inside.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] In this heat exchanger section, the refrigerant goes through multiple tube passes, which are surrounded by heat transfer fins through which cooling air can circulate from outside to inside the unit.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] There is a motorized fan inside the condenser unit near the top, which is covered by some grating to keep any objects from accidentally falling inside on the fan.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The fan is used to pull outside cooling air in through the heat exchanger section at the sides and blow it out the top through the grating.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] These condenser units are located on the outside of the building they are trying to cool, with tubing between the unit and building, one for vapor refrigerant entering and another for liquid refrigerant leaving the unit.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] Of course, an electric power supply is needed for the compressor and fan inside the unit.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] In a *direct-contact condenser*, hot vapor and cool liquid are introduced into a vessel and allowed to mix directly, rather than being separated by a barrier such as the wall of a heat exchanger tube.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The vapor gives up its latent heat and condenses to a liquid, while the liquid absorbs this heat and undergoes a temperature rise.
[src:condenser-heat-transfer/condenser-heat-transfer] The entering vapor and liquid typically contain a single condensable substance, such as a water spray being used to cool air and adjust its humidity.
